{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13895"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13895"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.63,0.04,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6514"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13895"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2341"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47523"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman is admitted for inpatient rehabilitation following a hemiarthroplasty procedure for a fractured neck of femur following a fall. On day five of admission the patient becomes increasingly agitated and confused over the period of a few hours. The patient, who was previously cooperative, is now trying to get out of bed and is not responding to verbal redirection. An increase in urinary frequency was noted earlier that evening, though the patient did not comment on any abdominal pain or dysuria. The patient has a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications include metformin, lisinopril, and paracetamol. She is a non-smoker and has one to two glasses of red wine with dinner, several nights per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She is disorientated to time and place. There are no focal neurological deficits. Heart and lung examinations are unremarkable. There is no neck stiffness. Her cannula site is unremarkable and she has no visible skin lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer haloperidol for agitation","Order an urgent CT brain","Perform blood cultures and urine dipstick","Transfer to a well-lit room","Administer thiamine and benzodiazepine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in this scenario is to perform a septic screen which should include \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood cultures and a urine dipstick\u003C/strong\u003E, as well as review all cannula sites and for skin lesions. Multiple sets of blood cultures should be taken if possible, as the diagnostic yield increases significantly. In reality, full blood count and biochemistry should also be taken at the same time as the blood culture (instead of with the morning blood round). One should also consider a viral swab/ covid RAT, chest x-ray and sending a urine culture if there are any indications the relevant systems are involved. This patient\u0027s sudden change in mental status, accompanied by fever, strongly suggests an underlying infection. In elderly patients, infections often present atypically, with confusion or agitation being a common manifestation, especially in urinary tract infections (UTIs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E for agitation would be inappropriate without first identifying and treating the underlying cause. Antipsychotics should be used cautiously in elderly patients due to the risk of side effects and potential worsening of delirium. Obviously if the patient\u0027s confusion and agitation does not facilitate the collection of samples for analysis, then it might be more prudent to give some form of sedation first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile an \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent CT brain\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered to rule out intracranial pathology, the presence of fever and the acute onset of symptoms make an infection more likely as the initial differential diagnosis. A CT brain may be considered if the patient does not improve with initial management or if focal neurological signs develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to a well-lit room\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if her problem was thought to be one of confusion alone. However, in the circumstances described, the first action must be to consider underlying sepsis and perform a septic screen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering thiamine and benzodiazepine\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if alcohol withdrawal was suspected. However, given the patient\u0027s moderate drinking history and the presence of fever, alcohol withdrawal is less likely to be the primary cause of her symptoms. In cases where alcohol withdrawal is confirmed or highly suspected the Alcohol Withdrawal Scale (AWS), a six-item scale for assessing the clinical course of alcohol withdrawal, or other similar clinical scales can be used to assess the severity of alcohol withdrawal syndrome, and can provide clinical guidance to the dose of benzodiazepines that may be required. However, diazepam can worsen delirium, particularly in elderly patients, by causing excessive sedation, increasing confusion, and potentially masking important clinical signs. Therefore, it should be used cautiously and only when alcohol withdrawal is confirmed or highly suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn elderly patients, it is crucial to maintain a high index of suspicion for infection when there are sudden behavioural changes or altered mental status, even if typical symptoms of infection are absent. Urinary tract infections, in particular, are a common cause of confusion in older adults. By performing a urine dipstick in many patients it will be possible to quickly identify a potential infection and initiate appropriate antibiotic therapy, which is essential for improving the patient\u0027s condition and preventing further complications. Other diagnostics such as blood cultures will take some time to return, however have a higher diagnostic yield if taken prior to commencement of any empirical antimicrobial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fever in elderly patients can commonly result in a change in sensorium ranging from lethargy to agitation.","Behavioural changes in elderly patients should be considered a warning sign to look for an underlying infection.","Urinary tract infections are a common cause of altered mental status in elderly patients."],"references":["Fong TG, Tulebaev SR, Inouye SK. Delirium in elderly adults: diagnosis, prevention and treatment. Nat Rev Neurol. 2009 Apr;5(4):210-20. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3065676/","Atterton B, Paulino MC, Povoa P, Martin-Loeches I. Sepsis Associated Delirium. Medicina (Kaunas). 2020 May 18;56(5):240. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7279289/","Williams D, Lewis J, McBride A. A comparison of rating scales for the alcohol-withdrawal syndrome. Alcohol and Alcoholism. 2001;36(2):104-8. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/alcalc/article/36/2/104/278540","Sachdeva A, Choudhary M, Chandra M. Alcohol Withdrawal Syndrome: Benzodiazepines and Beyond. J Clin Diagn Res. 2015 Sep;9(9):VE01-VE07. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4606320/#:~:text=Benzodiazepines%20(BZD)%20are%20the%20mainstay,the%20preferred%20treatment%20for%20AWS.","Management of Withdrawal from Alcohol and Other Drugs: Clinical Guidance. In: NSW Health [online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/aod/professionals/Pages/clinical-guidance.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T09:16:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T09:16:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6514"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up